      "cardText": "SHAME SPIRAL CARD: Comparing to other survivors\n\n1) WHAT HAPPENED NOW\nEnvironment: Group/social\nTrigger: Comparing to other survivors\n\n2) THE OLD TRAUMA STORY\n“I am behind”\n\n3) WHAT SHAME MAY SAY\n“There is something wrong with me for reacting this way.”\n\n4) BODY SIGNALS\nshame\n\n5) DEFAULT PROTECTION PATTERN\nfold/collapse | Arousal: mixed | Risk: 🟠 Moderate\n\n6) OLD ORIGIN THIS MAY ECHO\nOld survival learning: the nervous system learned that self-blame was safer than uncertainty.\n\n7) WHAT IS MORE TRUE\nA trigger is a signal, not a verdict. This reaction makes sense, and I can check present evidence before I obey shame.\n\n8) RE-PARENTING RESPONSE\nReduce the task. Food, water, warmth, and one safe person come before analysis.\n\n9) REPAIR STEP\nDo the grounding step first: Different nervous systems, different pace. Then write one sentence: 'The shame said __, but the present evidence says __.'\n\n10) PARTNER / CLINICIAN RESPONSE\nValidate the feeling, do not debate the shame story, and help the person return to one concrete next step.\n\n11) PAKISTAN / CULTURAL NOTE\nModerate cultural relevance; check whether family, class, gender, religion, or workplace hierarchy changes how this trigger is experienced.\n\n12) USE THIS MODULE\nRough-Day Protocol",
